            <p>The letter brings us a good discussion about diverse values for the planning of nature in cities. In this sense, this is an interesting topic that should be more explored in the decision-making of urban greenery. However, it brings out a discussion that is not new in terms of the Nature Futures Framework from IPBES for urban nature and should be included in the background:&#x00a0;e.g., Mansur, 
                <italic>et al.</italic> "Nature futures for the urban century: Integrating multiple values into urban management."&#x00a0;
                <italic>Environmental Science &amp; Policy</italic>&#x00a0;131 (2022): 46-56.&#x00a0;https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1462901122000193
                <sup>
                    <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="rep-ref-35205-1">1</xref>
                </sup>.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> I would recommend also to include more citations to corroborate the statements. For instance the 4th paragraph of the Background, "As climate change progresses..." There is a lot of evidence on that, a citation is needed. Also in the rest of this paragraph, there are important contributions in the area to be cited on how urban greenery enhances human well-being and the impacts of the lack of it.&#x00a0;</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The same for&#x00a0;Nature-Based Solutions, there are many important contributions in the area and some evidence is needed. For instance,&#x00a0;https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/science.abn9668
                <sup>
                    <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="rep-ref-35205-2">2</xref>
                </sup>.&#x00a0;</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> In the discussion part, it is important to give more practical examples of what nature as a culture would look like and the benefits of that to human well-being and biodiversity in cities corroborated with evidence in the literature.&#x00a0;</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> As the audience of this letter seems to be urban planners and decision-makers, the benefits/advantages for the city of having more nature as culture should be explicitly discussed. Maybe bring some numbers and statistical comparisons on the relationship of, for example, community gardening as nature as culture, health, and local food supply, or something similar.</p>
            <p>Where applicable, are recommendations and next steps explained clearly for others to follow? (Please consider whether others in the research community would be able to implement guidelines or recommendations and/or constructively engage in the debate)</p>
            <p>No</p>
